===Etymology===
From {{etyl|fro}} {{term|cresme}} (modern: ''[[crème]]''), blend of {{LL.}} {{term|chrisma}} "ointment" (from {{etyl|el}} {{term|chrisma}} "unguent"), and {{LL.}} {{term|cramum}} "cream", perhaps from {{Gau.}}. Replaced {{etyl|ang}} ''ream''. Borrowed again from {{etyl|fr}} in the 1800s, as {{term|creme}}. Figurative sense of "most excellent element or part" appears from 1581. Verb meaning "to beat, thrash, wreck" is 1929, U.S. colloquial.

